# iOS Native Development Guidelines for ResursYellow

## Core Principles
- ALWAYS follow Apple Human Interface Guidelines (HIG)
- Use ONLY native SwiftUI and UIKit components
- Implement liquid glass (glassmorphism) effects for modern iOS aesthetics
- Prioritize native iOS design patterns and user experience

## SwiftUI Best Practices

### Design System
- Use SF Symbols for all icons (never custom icon fonts or images unless absolutely necessary)
- Utilize native iOS color system: `.primary`, `.secondary`, `.tertiary`, `Color(uiColor: .systemBlue)`, etc.
- Implement Dynamic Type for accessibility
- Support both light and dark mode with semantic colors
- Use native spacing: `.padding()`, `.spacing()` with standard values (8, 12, 16, 20, 24, 32)

### Liquid Glass / Glassmorphism Effects
- Use `UIBlurEffect` with materials like `.systemUltraThinMaterial`, `.systemThinMaterial`, `.systemMaterial`
- Apply `.background(.ultraThinMaterial)`, `.background(.thinMaterial)`, `.background(.regularMaterial)`, `.background(.thickMaterial)` for SwiftUI
- For custom glassmorphism: combine blur effects with `.opacity()` and `.background()` modifiers
- Use translucent backgrounds with blur: `UIColor.black.withAlphaComponent(0.6)` + blur effect
- Implement vibrancy effects with `UIVibrancyEffect` when needed

### Navigation & Layout
- Use native navigation: `NavigationStack`, `NavigationLink`, `NavigationSplitView` for iPad
- Implement `TabView` for tab-based navigation (never custom tab bars unless essential)
- Use `List` and `Form` for structured content
- Use `ScrollView` with native scroll behaviors
- Follow iOS safe area guidelines with `.ignoresSafeArea()` only when intentional

### Components & Controls
- Use native controls: `Button`, `Toggle`, `Picker`, `Slider`, `Stepper`, `TextField`, `SecureField`
- Implement `Menu` for contextual actions
- Use `.swipeActions()` for list item actions
- Apply native button styles: `.buttonStyle(.bordered)`, `.buttonStyle(.borderedProminent)`, `.buttonStyle(.plain)`
- Use `.confirmationDialog()` and `.alert()` for user confirmations

### Animations & Transitions
- Use native transitions: `.transition(.slide)`, `.transition(.opacity)`, `.transition(.scale)`
- Apply spring animations: `.animation(.spring(response: 0.3, dampingFraction: 0.7))` or `.spring`
- Use `.withAnimation()` for state-driven animations
- Implement gesture-driven interactions with `.gesture()` modifiers
- Follow iOS motion guidelines (respect reduced motion accessibility setting)

### Visual Effects
- Apply corner radius with `.clipShape(RoundedRectangle(cornerRadius: X))` or `.cornerRadius()`
- Use iOS standard corner radii: 8, 10, 12, 16, 20
- Implement shadows with `.shadow(color:radius:x:y:)` sparingly (iOS prefers elevation through blur/material)
- Use `.overlay()` and `.background()` for layering
- Apply `.blendMode()` when needed for special visual effects

### Performance & State Management
- Use `@State`, `@Binding`, `@StateObject`, `@ObservedObject`, `@EnvironmentObject` appropriately
- Prefer `@StateObject` for object creation, `@ObservedObject` for passed objects
- Use `@Environment` for system values and custom environment values
- Implement async/await for asynchronous operations
- Use `.task()` modifier for async work tied to view lifecycle

### Accessibility
- Always provide accessibility labels: `.accessibilityLabel()`, `.accessibilityHint()`
- Use `.accessibilityElement(children: .combine)` for grouping
- Support VoiceOver with meaningful descriptions
- Respect Dynamic Type with `.dynamicTypeSize()` limits when needed
- Support Reduce Motion with `@Environment(\.accessibilityReduceMotion)`
- Ensure color contrast meets WCAG guidelines

### Data Display
- Use `List` with proper list styles: `.listStyle(.insetGrouped)`, `.listStyle(.plain)`, `.listStyle(.sidebar)`
- Implement pull-to-refresh with `.refreshable()`
- Use `LazyVStack`/`LazyHStack` for performance in ScrollViews
- Apply proper loading states with `ProgressView()`
- Handle empty states with meaningful messaging

### Modals & Sheets
- Use `.sheet()` for modal presentations
- Use `.fullScreenCover()` for full screen modals
- Implement `.presentationDetents()` for custom sheet heights
- Use `.presentationDragIndicator()` for sheet dismissal indication
- Apply `.interactiveDismissDisabled()` when necessary

## UIKit Integration (When Needed)

### When to Use UIKit
- For features not yet available in SwiftUI
- When fine-grained control over UIKit components is required
- Use `UIViewRepresentable` or `UIViewControllerRepresentable` for bridging

### Appearance Customization
- Configure appearance using `UIAppearance` API in `onAppear` of root view or App init
- Use `UINavigationBarAppearance`, `UITabBarAppearance`, `UIToolbarAppearance`
- Apply blur effects with `UIBlurEffect` and `UIVisualEffectView`

## Code Style

### Naming Conventions
- Use descriptive, Swift-style names: `camelCase` for variables/functions, `PascalCase` for types
- Name views with `View` suffix: `WalletView`, `TransactionDetailView`
- Name view models with `ViewModel` or `Manager`: `PocketsManager`

### File Organization
- One view per file
- Group related views in folders (Components, Models, Views, etc.)
- Use extensions for view modifiers and helper functions

### Comments & Documentation
- Add comments for complex logic only
- Use `// MARK: -` to organize code sections
- Document public APIs with triple-slash comments `///`

## Specific to This Project

### Tab Bar
- Maintain liquid glass effect on tab bar as implemented
- Use SF Symbols with filled variants for selected state
- Keep consistent color scheme (system blue for tint)

### Navigation
- Maintain current tab-based structure
- Use NavigationStack within each tab for hierarchical navigation
- Preserve environment objects across navigation

### Visual Theme
- Dark mode optimized with liquid glass effects
- Use blur materials for overlays and cards
- Maintain translucent backgrounds where appropriate
- Apply consistent corner radii and spacing

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid
- ❌ Never use custom tab bars when native TabView suffices
- ❌ Avoid hardcoded colors; use semantic color system
- ❌ Don't ignore safe areas unless intentionally designing full-bleed content
- ❌ Never use pixel values; use points and native spacing
- ❌ Avoid excessive shadows; prefer iOS-native elevation through materials
- ❌ Don't create custom navigation when native components work
- ❌ Never break iOS gestures (back swipe, sheet dismissal, etc.)
- ❌ Avoid fixed sizes; use flexible layouts with GeometryReader sparingly

## Testing & Preview
- Always provide SwiftUI previews with `#Preview`
- Test in both light and dark mode
- Preview different Dynamic Type sizes
- Test on different device sizes (iPhone SE, standard, Pro Max, iPad)

